question: Which body of water required more intensive man made barriers the Dundee Canal or Lake Worth Lagoon?

The Dundee Canal required more intensive man made barriers than Lake Worth Lagoon.  The Dundee Canal was a human-made structure, built for water control, flood prevention, irrigation, and water transport.  It was built between 1858 and 1861 and ran parallel to the Passaic River.  It supplied hydropower and water for manufacturing.  The canal was never used for navigational purposes, but there was interest by some members of the business community to modify the canal to support navigational uses.

On the other hand, Lake Worth Lagoon is a natural body of water, a lagoon located in southeastern Florida, United States, along the Atlantic coast.  The lagoon is separated from the Atlantic Ocean by a barrier island, and it is connected to the ocean through inlets.
